  "tables": [
    {
      "block_id": "1b94750c-f3ba-80ea-b1ec-e75c9927278d",
      "heading": "Abstract",
      "rows": [
        [
          "Task",
          "Context",
          "Teaching Method",
          "Student Performance Definition",
          "Target",
          "Students",
          "Courses",
          "Data sources",
          "Features",
          "Flaw of Previous Models",
          "Novelty of Model",
          "Preprocessing Details",
          "Models",
          "Assessment Strategy",
          "Performance Metric: Best Model",
          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "MOOC",
          "E-Learning",
          "Score on Next Graded Learning Material\n",
          "Above Median/Below Median ",
          "3000 generated students\n1000 students on Canvas",
          "Each dataset refers to one course",
          "Assignments,\nDiscussions, \nVideo Lecture Views",
          "[Sequences of Activities]",
          "Current knowledge models tend to avoid relationships between different types of learning materials. \n\nCurrent measures (such as time spent on specific resources) may indicate contradictory realities. \n\n",
          "The proposed model identifies relationships between different types of learning resources while, simultaneously, building a domain knowledge model that allows a better mapping of materials to their respective knowledge components. \n\nThis model follows an essential assumption: the knowledge provided by different types of learning materials can be described using the same latent space → meaning transferrability between types of learning materials.\n",
          "Each learning material as pre-assigned to a specific knowledge components.\n\nLearners are represented by a tensor of 3-lower dimensional representations:\n\n1. Latent Features\n\n2. A temporal dynamic knowledge tensor\n\n3. A mapping between materials and different knowledge concepts.\n\nThe preoduct between Knowledge Tensor T and Latent Feature _Matrix S represents the student’s knowledge in each concept before an attempt.\n\n",
          "Individual BKT,\nDKT\nDeedback-Driven Tensor Factorization, \nTensor Factorization Without Learning,\nBayesian Probabilistic Tensor Factorization, \nAverage of All Predictions, \nMulti-View Knowledge Model\n",
          "5-Fold Cross-Validation",
          "Synthetic Dataset-1\n\n{RMSE: 0.1388 - MVKM, MAE: 0.1049 - MVKM}\n\nSynthetic Dataset-2\n\n{RMSE: 0.2221 - MVKM, MAE: 0.1739 - MVKM}\n\nSynthetic Dataset-3\n\n{RMSE: 0.1532 - MVKM, MAE: 0.1171 - MVKM}\n\nMORF-QD\n\n{RMSE: 2088 - MVKM, MAE: 0.1603 - MVKM}\n\nMORF_QL\n\n{RMSE: 0.2150 - MVKM, MAE: 0.1654 - MVKM}\n\nCANVAS_H\n\n{RMSE: 0.0613 - MVKM, MAE: 0.0362 - MVKM}",
          "For each model, the probability is assumed to be the predicted score on each exercise.\n\nTo do that, the authors benchmark their models in 6 distinct datasets: 3 synthetic datasets and 3 real datasets.\n\nTests include some form of hyper-parameter tuning via Grid Search. Model includes constraint for learning and forgetting materials. Results show that these constraints, while not universal, are important constructs to consider in knowledge modelling,",
          "All datasets are done on a MOOC/course specific analysis."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
